  "prompt": "What is the SAS syntax for calculating the output of a logit model?",
  "response": "In SAS, there are several ways to calculate the output of a logit model. Here's a typical approach:\n\n1. Basic Logistic Regression Syntax:\n```sas\nproc logistic data=dataset;\n   model dependent_var = independent_vars;\n   output out=output_dataset pred=predicted_prob;\nrun;\n```\n\n2. More Detailed Version:\n```sas\nproc logistic data=dataset;\n   model dependent_var = independent_vars / link=logit;\n   output out=output_dataset \n          pred=predicted_prob \n          predclose=lower_ci \n          predclose=upper_ci;\nrun;\n```\n\nKey components:\n- `proc logistic`: Specifies logistic regression procedure\n- `model`: Defines dependent and independent variables\n- `output`: Creates an output dataset\n- `pred=`: Generates predicted probabilities\n- `link=logit`: Specifies logit link function (default)\n\n3. With Additional Options:\n```sas\nproc logistic data=dataset;\n   class categorical_vars / param=reference;\n   model dependent_var = independent_vars / \n          selection=stepwise \n          details;\n   output out=output_dataset \n          prob=predicted_prob;\nrun;\n```\n\nThe specific syntax may vary depending on your exact requirements.",
